<p><i><b>Kigo</b></i> <span style="font-weight: normal">(<span class="t_nihongo_kanji"><span lang="ja" xml:lang="ja">季語</span></span> <span class="t_nihongo_comma" style="display:none">,</span><i><span class="t_nihongo_romaji">"season word"</span></i><span class="t_nihongo_help noprint"><sup><a href="/wiki/Help:Japanese" title="Help:Japanese"><span class="t_nihongo_icon" style="color: #00e; font: bold 80% sans-serif; text-decoration: none; padding: 0 .1em;">?</span></a></sup></span>)</span> (plural <i>kigo</i>) is a word or phrase associated with a particular <a href="/wiki/Season" title="Season">season</a>, used in <a href="/wiki/Japanese_poetry" title="Japanese poetry">Japanese poetry</a>. Kigo are used in the collaborative linked-verse forms <a href="/wiki/Renga" title="Renga">renga</a> and <a href="/wiki/Renku" title="Renku">renku</a>, as well as in <a href="/wiki/Haiku" title="Haiku">haiku</a>, to indicate the season referred to in the <a href="/wiki/Stanza" title="Stanza">stanza</a>. They are valuable in providing economy of expression.</p>
